3/30/2022

This data of international teams was collected between February 16th, 2022 and April 23, 2022. Thank you Harry Kim for filling out most of the CSV. Please not that data is constantly changing through time, and ou r data should be most representative of national team setups based on November 2021 and data based on April 2022.

Question: How much influence does international caps have on a players transfer value based on the best 6 teams in Europe? We have created a dataset for a total of 126 players, which mostly consist of players included in the latest international team setups (November 2021) of five European national teams, Spain, England, France, Germany, and Italy. In collecting data for our numerical variables, we used reliable sources such as soccerdatabase, transfermarkt, and we used salarysport for collecting information on wages for the players included in our study. We chose only European teams and independent variables due to regional/cultural similarities and convenience.

What is a cap, why did we choose it, and how is it significant?: International caps is a football/soccer term to describe a player logging playing time for their international team during a game. Only the best players will be called up to be able to represent the country. Basically, a cap allows you to become a representative of your country for the most popular sport in the world. They are a big deal in the sport as it is regarded as one of the highest honors so this was one of the subconscious reasons why our group chose this variable of interest to test.

Variables:

  • Players - Player name (First Last)

  • Nationality - Country that a player plays for internationally through FIFA

  • Club - Team that a player plays for

  • Position - The primary position of a player: goalkeeper (GK), defender (DF), midfielder (MF), or forward (FW)

  • Age - How old a player is at the time of taking our data

Value (aka Transfer Value) - What a player should theoretically sell for in the transfer market if another team wanted to buy the player based on transfermarkt.us (in and in millions). Value is primarily based on a players age, potential, skill, in-game performance, and much more.

For more detail on how transfermarkt determines value, read https://www.transfermarkt.co.in/transfermarkt-market-value-explained-how-is-it-determined-/view/news/385100.

  • Wage - Amount of money a player earns (in and in thousands) via salarysport.com.

  • Caps - Amount of international games a player has played for their country (only applies if player participates in the game and does not count if they just get called up and sits on the bench)

In order to check whether we can use linear regression for our data, we need to check some assumptions and we start with checking for equal variance. (assumptions learned from STA 141A at UCD): https://www.godatadrive.com/blog/basic-guide-to-test-assumptions-of-linear-regression-in-r

We see that the variances of the factor level means look a little similar for each variable. While given small number of observations, the variation in the dotplots of each groups observations seems similar (might be randomness). We move on to check if theres linear relationship, residual errors having mean of 0 and constant variance, and normal distribution.

We can set up a correlation matrix to see if there are correlations between our variable of interest Value and their independent variable counterparts. We can also use it to see how these indepedent variables affect one another as well. We can see Age and Caps are highly correlated to each other.

Earlier, we limited our linear regression to quantitative data up until the correlation matrix. The independent variable of player position is also a factor that determines player value. The plot with the Position variable messes up the Residuals vs.Fitted so instead of using Position in our model since it messes up our linear regression, we will use plots to determine how position affects value.

Conclusion: Its hard to determine if there is statistically significant correlation between player value and international caps. The linear regression models and correlation matrix we used determined that caps are not all that important to determining player value for the best 6 teams in Europe. The caps variable in modelall shows that the caps variable isnt statistically significant since it has 0 stars in the summary function. The \(R^2\) of modelcaps is very low since its the model that excludes the more important variables for determining player value.

Even without statistical data, caps not being highly correlated to player value makes sense in real life. Other aspects such as potential (player ceilings), work rate, hype, player nationality, and many other factors determine value better than international caps. They are not the greatest indicator since the best of a countrys players play and that causes the second best player in that position to not get caps in favor of the best player. For example, think of the second string players who play behind superstars like Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo. These players are great in their own right, but they are overshadowed by greater players. This scenario happens with every team and the national teams we have chosen for this dataset are no exception. We were not able to get a perfect model to determine player value, but player age and player wage makes up 46% of the predicting power to estimate player value, very nice.

As we can see with our bubble charts, we have more evidence to back up our claim that caps is not a good indicator for determining a players transfer value. Caps is not a good indicator for determining player value as there are better options to determine value from.
